.SH NAME
AnalyserNode.maxDecibels \- AnalyserNode: maxDecibels property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]maxDecibels\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]AnalyserNode\f[R] interface is a double value representing the
maximum power value in the scaling range for the FFT analysis data, for
conversion to unsigned byte values \[em] basically, this specifies the
maximum value for the range of results when using
\f[CR]getByteFrequencyData()\f[R].
.SH VALUE
A double, representing the maximum \c
.UR https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decibel
decibel
.UE \c
\ value for scaling the FFT analysis data, where \f[CR]0\f[R] dB is the
loudest possible sound, \f[CR]\-10\f[R] dB is a 10th of that, etc.
The default value is \f[CR]\-30\f[R] dB.
.PP
When getting data from \f[CR]getByteFrequencyData()\f[R], any
frequencies with an amplitude of \f[CR]maxDecibels\f[R] or higher will
be returned as \f[CR]255\f[R].
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]IndexSizeError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if a value less than or equal to
\f[CR]AnalyserNode.minDecibels\f[R] is set.
.SH EXAMPLES
The following example shows basic usage of an \f[CR]AudioContext\f[R] to
create an \f[CR]AnalyserNode\f[R], then \f[CR]requestAnimationFrame\f[R]
and \f[CR]<canvas>\f[R] to collect frequency data repeatedly and draw a
\[lq]winamp bar graph style\[rq] output of the current audio input.
